# Tricks/SplitForSet.elm — WORKHORSE

SPLIT_FOR_SET: a hand card of value V finds two extractable
same-value, different-suit board cards, and the three
together form a new 3-card set.

## Status

- **Label:** WORKHORSE. Stable.
- **Go counterpart ripped 2026-04-20** (`project_hints_are_client_side.md`).

## Algorithm

For each hand card `hc`:
1. Scan board for cards at `hc.value` with a DIFFERENT suit
   AND `canExtract` at that position. Collect as candidates.
2. If fewer than 2 candidates, skip.
3. `pickTwoDistinctSuits` picks the FIRST two candidates
   with distinct suits that AREN'T `hc.suit`. (Going first,
   we skip candidates matching `hc.suit` — a set must have
   three distinct suits.)
4. Classify the trio `[hc.card, a.card, b.card]`. Accept
   only if `Set`.

## First-match ordering

`pickTwoDistinctSuits` iterates candidates in board-scan
order. This makes the output deterministic and matches Go.

## Apply-time safety

Two `relocate` + `extractCard` rounds, each refusing on any
failure:
1. Relocate target A; extract. Refuse on failure.
2. Relocate target B on the updated board; extract. Refuse
   on failure.

Then push a new stack with `[freshlyPlayed hc, extA, extB]`
at `dummyLoc`. Note: unlike `PeelForRun`, the stack
construction here does NOT sort by value — sets don't care
about order. Go matches.

## Why B may fail after A extracted

If target A was peeled from the middle of a run,
`extractCard` splits the run into two halves. Target B might
have been in a now-too-short half, losing `canExtract`
eligibility. The re-relocate on `board2` catches this.

## Key exports

- `trick : Trick` — `id = "split_for_set"`, description:
  "Take two same-value cards out of the board and form a
  new set with your hand card."

